highlights.description: The floods in Madison in August 2018 were devastating to many. This woman tells a story about losing her home.
Woman her lost her home in August 2018 floods talks about neighbors pulling together and her love for her neighborhood.

This person talking about how people care here in Madison, wondering if that is a Midwestern thing. Is it unique to the MW? With LVN we can listen in to other places to see what caring looks like elsewhere.
Anne talks about how neighbors work together to keep the flowers on the bike path through Dudgen-Monroe beautiful
Anne and Jason become friends through their LVN conversation
Anne talks about the trend toward high-end apartment buildings in Madison applies to senior housing, too.
Many people in Madison comment on the need for better public transportation here. This man notes the need is acute for those who get off work late at night
Former hotel manager talks about seeing employees struggle with transportation. Madison is on an isthmus, and that strip of land isn't getting wider.
"It's getting more and more expensive to be poor in Madison."
Madison continues to struggle with serious racial divisions. This participant talks about another: local Madison vs. education and university Madison.
"I was grateful that I was poor because I was around other brown people...people who were in my situation."
Alex talks about what it feels like to be a Black student at Edgewood, a predominantly white institution.
Students of color so often are asked to help repair the racism in their colleges and universities. This student talks about the injustice of that.
Alex commenting that when the flooding happened that took Anne's home, he couldn't relate, because her perceived it was mainly affecting affluent people.
...and yet, he empathizes with Anne's loss.
